uary 1074","0985":"0985","1038":"1038","0995":"0995","about 1066":"about 1066","Longueville, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Longueville, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","Lassy, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Lassy, Calvados, Normandy, France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Falaise, Calvados, Normandie, France":"Falaise, Calvados, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lacy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Lassy in Calvados, named from a Gaulish personal name <i>Lascius</i> (of uncertain origin and meaning) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lasee","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English or Irish   Lacy  ."]},{"name":"Lacey","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Lacy  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh de Lacy Lord of Lassy was born on 6 October 1020, in Lassy, Calvados, Normandy, France, his father, Roland de Lassy I, was 25 and his mother, Adèle  de EU, was 36. He had at least 1 daughter with Emma du Bois-l'Évêque. He died on 27 March 1085, in Normandy, France, at the age of 64."},"et":{"6 October 1020–27 March 1085":"6. oktoober 1020–27. märts 1085","1020–1085":"1020–1085","1022–1074":"1022–1074","1038–1094":"1038–1094","0995–1060":"0995–1060","0985–1066":"0985–1066","1066":"1066","1022":"1022","27 March 1085":"27. märts 1085","1020":"1020","1074":"1074","1085":"1085","6 October 1020":"6. oktoober 1020","1050":"1050","1094":"1094","1060":"1060","28 January 1074":"28. jaanuar 1074","0985":"0985","1038":"1038","0995":"0995","about 1066":"umbes 1066","Longueville, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Longueville, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Lassy, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Lassy, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Falaise, Calvados, Normandie, France":"Falaise, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"6 October 1020–27 March 1085":"6. lokakuuta 1020–27. maaliskuuta 1085","1020–1085":"1020–1085","1022–1074":"10